In related news, this code is completely bogus:
```
TReal x, y, z;
```
Since x, y and z are not in an array it's UB to try to get at y and z by adding stuff to x. The compiler would be well within its rights to decide that `operator[]` can't possibly read from anything but x and always return the value of x.

The correct code would be:
```
union {
  TReal values[3];
  struct {
    TReal x, y, z;
  };
};
```
and then use `values[i]` in `operator[]`. This would be an API change and I think some compilers complain about anonymous struct/union.

@samuelcolvin Currently MonkeyType doesn't raise errors on a mismatch. You can generate a stub that ignores existing annotations using `--ignore-existing-annotations` option (or corresponding kwarg to `build_stubs_from_traces`). I suppose a hacky way would be to try to apply such a stub with retype, which would fail on any mismatch.

I'm curious what you're thinking about the purpose of the plugin, though. I assumed the purpose was to collect traces while running tests, not to verify accuracy of existing annotations.

I would like to improve MonkeyType's usefulness for verifying accuracy of existing annotations, but I'm worried that there will be a lot of false positives if this is done in an automated way (since often MonkeyType's annotations need to be hand-improved, e.g. to use less restrictive abstract or interface types instead of concrete types, to add generics or overloads, etc). So currently I don't have a better idea for this than that you run `monkeytype stub --ignore-existing-annotations` and then compare by hand.

