For posterity:

@rtibbles and I spent some time chatting about whether we could get rid of the meta-programming entirely because it increases the difficulty of onboarding new people into the build system and debugging issues. Personally, I believe that using dynamic `require` statements or `import()` statements would be much cleaner than doing our own code generation because it's handled by the library instead of us. If we could set the dynamic load `context` based on a single source of truth (e.g. _supported_languages.json_) then everything would be rosy. However we're currently using Bublé, which doesn't support this.

So... the verdict was that this PR could be improved a bit by at least checking the generated code into git. This means that the build system doesn't rely on weird stubbed out virtual modules that need to be ignored by eslint, and people can inspect the code that's run directly.

