@woodcockr, I meant non-lazy version, the one that actually allocates all the needed memory, eventually. That version simply can not succeed if too much is requested and so should fail sooner. Note that process can still fail with "out of memory" errors, even when main data store has been allocated successfully.

The "lazy version",  the one that uses dask is a separate issue. The whole point of that one is to pretend to have all the data loaded, but only load chunks of data as they are needed.

There is no magical "load into distributed memory" option, unless you use "dask" version that way I guess, maybe..
